Consequently, the difference between the CT
                         and the Co
                         can be used to calculate the diffusion-controlled capacitance (Ci
                        ) based on Eq. (13). It was found that the diffusion-controlled capacitance predominantly contributed between 77.1-95.8% of the total capacitance (Table 2
                        ). The 10-CDT electrode in 2-CDK electrolyte had the highest diffusion-controlled capacitance of 95.8%, which agrees well with its highest areal specific capacitance. This is consistent with the analysis using the Cottrell's and Randles-Sevcik's methods that the CDs enhanced the diffusion process of charge transport, giving rise to higher supercapacitor performance.

To the best of our knowledge, the areal specific capacitance of our supercapacitor (2,200 mF cm−2) is the best and at least four times better than the previously reported TiO2 composite supercapacitors (Fig. 8c and Table 3
                        ). Furthermore, it is also higher than many of those obtained from the more expensive, widely studied RuO2 and MnO2 
                        [76-79]. The Ragone plot of 10-CDT electrode in KOH and 2-CDK electrolytes are presented in Fig. 8d. The 10-CDT electrode in 2-CDK electrolyte produced higher areal energy density than the 10-CDT electrode in pure KOH electrolyte, in which the highest values for energy density and power density are 51.3 µWh cm−2 and 635 µW cm−2, respectively. From this work, the CDs have been proved to be potent electrode and electrolyte additives with potential for the fabrication of high-performance, low-cost supercapacitors. With a combination of simplicity, low cost, and ultrahigh-performance, the supercapacitors developed in this work are considered to be the most practical ones.
